#### Function for printing separator line
def separator(n):
    print("\n","="*n,"\n")

### Function for reading a csv file if location or file path is given
def read_data(file_path):
    return pd.read_csv(file_path)

### function for printing number of unique elements and unique values in columns 
def unique_ele(data,col):
    for c in col:
        print("The number of unique elements in column",c,data[c].nunique())
        print("The unique values in column",c,data[c].unique())
        print("The values counts of columns",c)
        print(data[c].value_counts())
        separator(75)

### function for printing inference
def infer(value,n=50):
    print("\nInference:\n")
    print(value)
    separator(n)
    
###Function to treat outliers
def treat_outliers(data):
    q1 = np.percentile(data,25)
    q3 = np.percentile(data,75)
    iqr = q3-q1
    upper = q3 + (iqr*1.5)
    lower = q1 - (iqr*1.5)
    for i in range(0,len(data)):
        if (data[i]>upper):
            data[i] = upper
        elif (data[i]<lower):
            data[i]=lower
    return data

Modelling¶

In [261]:
### Defining the crime columns into x variable
x = data.iloc[::,1:]

## Calling the KMeans Model and defining into cluster variable considering n_clusters as 2
cluster = KMeans(n_clusters=2)

## Fitting the cluster variable 
cluster.fit(x)

### Predicting and storing into pred variable
pred = cluster.predict(x)

## Printing the predicted output
print("Predicted cluster values are:\n",pred)

### To determine the n_cluster value 
wcss = []
for i in range(1,10):
    km = KMeans(n_clusters=i,max_iter=50)
    km.fit(x)
    ## Calculate the squared errror and append in wcss variable
    wcss.append(km.inertia_) 
print("WCSS value for range 1 to 50 is...\n",wcss)

### Plotting to find the n_cluster value 
plt.figure(figsize=(15,7))
plt.title("Determine n_cluster Value")
plt.plot(wcss)
plt.show()
infer("The n value is 2 in this point only the error is min",125)

### storing the predivted op to the cluster 1 column in data
data['Cluster1'] = pred
print(data.head())

### Scatter plot for each columns in data
for i in range(1,len(data_col)-1):
    title= "Scatter plot for "+data_col[i]
    plt.figure(figsize=(5,5))
    plt.title(title)
    sns.scatterplot(data=data,y=data[data_col[i]],x=data['Location'],hue='Cluster1')
    plt.show()

### printing the value counts in percentage for clusters
print(data['Cluster1'].value_counts(normalize=True)*100)

### storing the lables of cluster into labels variable
labels= cluster.labels_

### silhouette_score is used to find the accuracy of the model
separator(50)
print("silhouette_score is ",silhouette_score(x,labels,metric='euclidean'))
infer("Our model has 59% accuracy")
